WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.840 --> 00:00:08.576
Let's plan something
nice for the weekend.

2
00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:10.760
seeing as I'm abandoning you
for the week.

3
00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:13.816
What do you fancy?
Dinner and a movie?

4
00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:16.520
-Date night?
-Yeah. a date night.

5
00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:21.256
I think if we're going to do a
date night. then we should stay in.

6
00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:23.696
And you can wear
that pretty blue dress.

7
00:00:23.720 --> 00:00:25.336
I'll get some strawberries
and cream.

8
00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:27.336
Are you cheap-skating me?

9
00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:29.160
I'm happy to buy some wine. too.

10
00:00:32.120 --> 00:00:34.856
Off to work with you!
I love you.

11
00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:38.240
Love you. too! Miss you already.
See you Saturday.

12
00:00:39.240 --> 00:00:41.040
I can't wait.

13
00:00:57.320 --> 00:00:59.040
How's it going?

14
00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:15.760
There you go.

15
00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:20.000
Good woman. Mam.

16
00:01:21.200 --> 00:01:23.359
You're doing brilliantly.

17
00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:12.480
How drunk were you. Chris?

18
00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:15.336
Emma?

19
00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:18.000
Show me that tattoo again.

20
00:02:39.240 --> 00:02:41.440
Bev Lyons.

21
00:02:47.480 --> 00:02:50.840
Bev and Chris.
what is your story?

22
00:03:28.760 --> 00:03:31.440
Jeez! What did that melon
ever do to you?

23
00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:35.216
-Melon? Nothing. Men... Ah!
-Oh!

24
00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:37.800
I take it you had that chat
with Harry B. then?

25
00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:41.376
Fergus.
relationships are overrated.

26
00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:44.479
I mean. since when did "fun"
become a dirty word?

27
00:03:45.760 --> 00:03:47.496
I mean. we agree
that we are grown-ups.

28
00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:49.776
It doesn't need
to be any more than it is.

29
00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:52.936
And then one of you wants the
other one to move to Australia.

30
00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:54.656
And who lives in Australia. anyway?

31
00:03:54.680 --> 00:03:56.816
Have you seen the size
of the spiders there?

32
00:03:56.840 --> 00:03:59.416
No. I am perfectly happy
where I am.

33
00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:02.136
Yeah. me. too. though I might just
move over to this side of the table.

34
00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:03.560
It's a bit safer.

35
00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:08.600
Look. relax.
I'm not going to hurt anybody.

36
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.976
-You get it. You miss Lola. right?
-What?

37
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:15.296
No. Not even thinking about her.

38
00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:17.880
Or that bloke she's seeing.
Ryan.

39
00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:20.656
Big. big. strong Ryan.

40
00:04:20.680 --> 00:04:23.480
You don't even know
if she's seeing him!

41
00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:26.696
Oh.

42
00:04:26.720 --> 00:04:28.576
Maybe he's a tactile guy?

43
00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:31.336
Oh. please!
Anyway. I don't care. right.

44
00:04:31.360 --> 00:04:33.856
I have a plan. I'm going
to move on with my life.

45
00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:36.256
Meet new people...

46
00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:39.176
Concentrate on work. right?
Like this case.

47
00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:43.240
Yeah. well. don't get too excited. He
told me barely anything on the phone.

48
00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:46.239
And he cuts up dead people
for a living.

49
00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:51.576
He's probably nuts.

50
00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:55.000
I'm picturing a fat little man
who smells of formaldehyde.

51
00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:00.360
Harry.

52
00:05:01.400 --> 00:05:04.160
Thank you so much
for agreeing to meet me.

53
00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:07.360
Any friend of Jordan's
is a friend of ours.

54
00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:10.000
Oh...

55
00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:13.400
Kitchen's just through here.

56
00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:26.496
Tattoos are pretty common.
though. right?

57
00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:28.736
I mean. fair enough.
maybe not musical bars.

58
00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:30.616
These weren't just
any musical bars.

59
00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:31.896
<i>Clair De Lune.</i>

60
00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:33.096
Debussy.

61
00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:35.736
Oh. I love that one!

62
00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:38.016
Here. what's that called
when they do that on a piano?

63
00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:39.880
Trill.

64
00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:43.056
At the end of <i>Clair De Lune.</i>

65
00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:46.896
there are four bars
of music with trills.

66
00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:49.216
Chris O'Neill.
that's the dead man.

67
00:05:49.240 --> 00:05:51.736
he had the third bar
tattooed on him.

68
00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:54.496
And the previous body
you remembered.

69
00:05:54.520 --> 00:05:56.776
Bev Lyons. she had the second?

70
00:05:56.800 --> 00:05:59.880
Yes. and she died
six months ago.

71
00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:03.336
So. two musical bars.
two accidental deaths -

72
00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:06.720
one by drowning.
another by a road accident?

73
00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:10.616
-That's too much chance.
-Is it. though?

74
00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:13.200
Couldn't it be just
one of those crazy quirks?

75
00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:15.816
I considered that until...

76
00:06:15.840 --> 00:06:18.016
Until you wondered
about the first bar.

77
00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:22.856
Yes. So. I went through all the
old files from my predecessor.

78
00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:26.000
well over 400.
until I found this.

79
00:06:26.520 --> 00:06:28.936
-Wow!
-Holy shit. that's not...?

80
00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:32.576
This post-mortem
is from 18 months ago.

81
00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:35.360
Same section of <i>Clair De Lune.</i>

82
00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:38.976
The opening bar.

83
00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:40.600
No way?

84
00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:43.976
Her name is Jess Boylan.

85
00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.376
Operation gone wrong.
Another accidental death.

86
00:06:48.400 --> 00:06:50.976
OK. that is weird.

87
00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.240
But it's not that easy. though to
make a murder look accidental.

88
00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:57.616
True.
but drowning's a good cover.

89
00:06:57.640 --> 00:07:00.856
And Chris.
he was severely drunk.

90
00:07:00.880 --> 00:07:04.296
Enough so I could believe he had
ethanol pumped into his veins.

91
00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:06.736
And Jess Boylan.
she died on the table.

92
00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:08.456
Entirely normal.

93
00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:11.336
but if somebody interfered
with a medical device...

94
00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:13.176
Totally doable.

95
00:07:13.200 --> 00:07:15.856
But it's unlikely
that there were three killers.

96
00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:19.240
More likely. if it's true.
one person behind it all.

97
00:07:21.080 --> 00:07:24.176
Do you know if these tattoos
were done before or after death?

98
00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:26.656
-Are you able to tell?
-Yeah.

99
00:07:26.680 --> 00:07:29.680
Not long before. in all cases.

100
00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:33.696
Three bars out of four?
And if they were murdered...

101
00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:35.719
There's another one to come.

102
00:07:37.280 --> 00:07:39.056
That's my fear.

103
00:07:39.080 --> 00:07:41.280
I have no time to lose.

104
00:07:46.920 --> 00:07:50.200
That's a lot of tattoo shops!

105
00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:02.760
I rarely get to talk about Jess
these days.

106
00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:07.760
People allow you so much time
to grieve and then. well...

107
00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:12.520
I'm a primary school teacher.
so it's a big smile every day.

108
00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:15.936
18 months or 18 days.
loss is still loss.

109
00:08:15.960 --> 00:08:18.800
Jess and I met
when we were teenagers.

110
00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:22.240
Our folks thought we were too
young to settle down. but...

111
00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:25.520
it didn't matter to us.

112
00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:29.376
But. um...
why are you so interested?

113
00:08:29.400 --> 00:08:32.376
I work as a consultant for
the state pathologist's office.

114
00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:35.240
We're investigating the
phenomenon of accidental deaths.

115
00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:39.800
Jess died during an operation.
wasn't it?

116
00:08:40.960 --> 00:08:42.400
Routine?

117
00:08:42.960 --> 00:08:47.336
Not at all. She. er...
She elected to get a tummy tuck.

118
00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:49.896
-Oh.
-It was insane.

119
00:08:49.920 --> 00:08:52.616
You never met
a more beautiful woman. but...

120
00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:56.176
no matter what I said.
she thought she was overweight.

121
00:08:56.200 --> 00:08:58.976
I wouldn't have changed
a hair on her body.

122
00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:01.736
She scheduled the surgery
in secret.

123
00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:04.960
And then it went wrong
and Jess bled to death.

124
00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:08.016
They said it was
a one-in-a-million possibility.

125
00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:11.240
Ironic.
given she was one in a million.

126
00:09:12.760 --> 00:09:15.096
She had a tattoo. didn't she?

127
00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:17.320
A musical signature?

128
00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:21.256
When did she get
that tattoo done. and why?

129
00:09:21.280 --> 00:09:22.736
While I was away.

130
00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:25.720
I'm not sure why.
She didn't play.

131
00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:29.360
I guess it was a part of her
changing the way she looked.

132
00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:33.376
Jess was into art. These are
her paintings on the wall.

133
00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:35.080
Oh. beautiful.

134
00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:40.216
Do you happen to know anyone
called Chris O'Neill or Bev Lyons?

135
00:09:40.240 --> 00:09:41.896
Mm-mm.

136
00:09:41.920 --> 00:09:44.776
Did Jess? I mean. could they be
work colleagues or...?

137
00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:46.456
Jess worked from home.

138
00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:48.896
She sold drawings
to animation studios.

139
00:09:48.920 --> 00:09:51.176
I've never heard
of a Chris or a Bev.

140
00:09:51.200 --> 00:09:53.816
Do you know where she had
that tattoo done?

141
00:09:53.840 --> 00:09:55.296
No.

142
00:09:55.320 --> 00:09:57.960
Is this really
all for some study?

143
00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:00.736
They're just weirdly
specific questions.

144
00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:02.840
Trust me. it's all related.

145
00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:21.896
-Not my work.
-Of course they're not.

146
00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:24.296
Look.
I've been doing this years.

147
00:10:24.320 --> 00:10:25.696
Right.

148
00:10:25.720 --> 00:10:27.760
Real artists.
they have a signature.

149
00:10:28.360 --> 00:10:31.656
And these? Well. they weren't
done by the same person.

150
00:10:31.680 --> 00:10:33.176
Well. at least this one.

151
00:10:33.200 --> 00:10:36.080
This was done
by one person in particular.

152
00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:38.976
See. tattooing is like art.

153
00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:40.816
You can spot an expert at work

154
00:10:40.840 --> 00:10:43.800
and this one here.
this is an expert.

155
00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:46.640
See the little flick
at the end of that line?

156
00:10:47.760 --> 00:10:49.680
That's an A.

157
00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:53.696
That's Jess Boylan's tattoo.
Have you ever heard of her?

158
00:10:53.720 --> 00:10:56.400
No. I can tell you
who did her tattoo. though.

159
00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:00.040
Apollo Connors.
He did one of mine.

160
00:11:00.640 --> 00:11:02.736
Thanks. man. This is brilliant!

161
00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:05.336
Yeah. you have a problem. though.

162
00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:07.816
-I do?
-Apollo is. er...

163
00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:09.736
odd.

164
00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:11.896
I love what I do. it's art.

165
00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:13.616
Apollo. though?

166
00:11:13.640 --> 00:11:16.440
He thinks he's Michelangelo
painting the Sistine Chapel.

167
00:11:17.160 --> 00:11:18.616
Better than. to be honest.

168
00:11:18.640 --> 00:11:21.976
Trust me.
I'm used to it not being easy.

169
00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:23.336
Are we doing or what this.
Setanta?

170
00:11:23.360 --> 00:11:25.616
I'm slipping into a coma here.

171
00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:29.640
So impatient!
Now. I'm gonna make it hurt.

172
00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:37.176
<i>Don't leave a message.
I won't bother to reply.</i>

173
00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:39.096
Hi. this is Fergus Reid.

174
00:11:39.120 --> 00:11:41.096
I wanted to speak to you
about Jess Boylan.

175
00:11:41.120 --> 00:11:43.439
My number should have
come up there...

176
00:11:45.240 --> 00:11:46.800
OK.

177
00:11:49.040 --> 00:11:50.376
-Hi. Harry?
<i>-Fergus?</i>

178
00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:52.576
I might have found
our tattoo artist.

179
00:11:52.600 --> 00:11:54.896
We might have a job
getting to speak to him.

180
00:11:54.920 --> 00:11:57.656
<i>Well. if you're at a loose end.
you can visit one of the families.</i>

181
00:11:57.680 --> 00:12:00.536
I've just done
Jess Boylan's husband.

182
00:12:00.560 --> 00:12:03.456
And he's never heard
of Bev or Chris.

183
00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:05.216
Right. so no help. then?

184
00:12:05.240 --> 00:12:07.496
<i>Other than being
completely grief-stricken</i>

185
00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:10.960
and reminding me why we do this
job in the first place. no help.

186
00:12:12.160 --> 00:12:14.176
If we can't find a link
between these victims

187
00:12:14.200 --> 00:12:16.976
I don't know how we'll identify
a potential fourth.

188
00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.296
OK. just. ah. send me the deets
of who I should chase up on.

189
00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:23.576
Details in-coming.

190
00:12:23.600 --> 00:12:27.440
Honestly!
Second-year English grad?

191
00:12:28.240 --> 00:12:30.400
Yeah. yeah. Whatever.

192
00:12:32.120 --> 00:12:33.120
Okay.

193
00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:38.880
Tell me. just looking for Sam?

194
00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:41.080
Cheers.

195
00:12:41.560 --> 00:12:43.440
Sam Robertson?

196
00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:46.616
You were engaged to Bev Lyons?

197
00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:47.896
What of it?

198
00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:49.816
Just need to ask
a few questions.

199
00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:52.016
Why would I want to talk
about that bitch?

200
00:12:52.040 --> 00:12:54.000
OK.

201
00:12:55.480 --> 00:12:58.176
I really don't know
if she'll be of any help to you.

202
00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:01.376
She's been non-communicative
for some time now.

203
00:13:01.400 --> 00:13:05.016
She came to us when she got too
bad for her son to take care of her.

204
00:13:05.040 --> 00:13:08.360
He was her full-time carer
for a while.

205
00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:12.056
He gave up his job.
everything to look after her.

206
00:13:12.080 --> 00:13:13.776
and then he died.

207
00:13:13.800 --> 00:13:16.640
Traffic accident. Very sad.

208
00:13:17.480 --> 00:13:19.176
No other family?

209
00:13:19.200 --> 00:13:21.800
-Not that we know of.
-No. me neither.

210
00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:28.440
Hello? Greta. is it?

211
00:13:29.720 --> 00:13:32.480
I'm Harry. I'm a friend
of your son's. Chris.

212
00:13:33.320 --> 00:13:36.136
Doctor.

213
00:13:36.160 --> 00:13:38.360
Yes. Greta. I'll get him.

214
00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.096
It's all she's said
since she arrived.

215
00:13:41.120 --> 00:13:44.680
The doctor sees her daily.
There's nothing wrong with her.

216
00:13:45.160 --> 00:13:48.040
Other than the dementia. obviously.

217
00:13:49.040 --> 00:13:52.080
Greta. I'm really sorry about
what happened to your son.

218
00:13:54.160 --> 00:13:56.280
Did you know he had a tattoo?

219
00:13:58.400 --> 00:13:59.600
Doctor?

220
00:14:00.320 --> 00:14:01.840
Doctor.

221
00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:07.656
Bev? Tattoo? Seems unlikely.

222
00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:10.456
Her body was a temple.
All that shit.

223
00:14:10.480 --> 00:14:13.400
Yeah. but you'd split up with
her. so you might not have known?

224
00:14:14.080 --> 00:14:15.640
Suppose.

225
00:14:16.520 --> 00:14:18.200
Why'd you break up?

226
00:14:18.760 --> 00:14:20.816
The line was
we weren't compatible.

227
00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:24.256
The truth is. Bev had everybody
convinced she was lovely.

228
00:14:24.280 --> 00:14:26.536
but she was a self-obsessed
narcissist

229
00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:28.216
that bled me dry for months

230
00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:30.816
while she was screwing
somebody at work. of course.

231
00:14:30.840 --> 00:14:32.840
She was always
screwing somebody at work.

232
00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:35.560
Oh. What did she do?

233
00:14:36.760 --> 00:14:38.616
Barrister was her day job.

234
00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:40.896
Loving herself was her main job.

235
00:14:40.920 --> 00:14:44.176
Woman was always banging on
about her health.

236
00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:46.280
I couldn't believe it
when she drowned.

237
00:14:46.680 --> 00:14:49.880
She was fitter than anybody.
I'll give her that.

238
00:14:50.360 --> 00:14:52.640
God works in mysterious ways.

239
00:14:53.920 --> 00:14:56.680
Did she know
either of these people?

240
00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:03.176
Don't know.

241
00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:05.640
Listen. you've to clear off.
I open up soon.

242
00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:09.600
All right. I'm going.

243
00:15:13.360 --> 00:15:15.600
If you remember anything.

244
00:15:18.560 --> 00:15:21.336
Hey. What's all this about?

245
00:15:21.360 --> 00:15:24.376
Her death was an accident.
Why are you asking questions?

246
00:15:24.400 --> 00:15:25.880
Research.

247
00:15:46.120 --> 00:15:49.160
This Sam. do you think he knew
Chris and Jess?

248
00:15:49.760 --> 00:15:52.456
I don't know. though when
he looked at their photos

249
00:15:52.480 --> 00:15:56.000
and claimed he didn't.
there was something on his face.

250
00:15:56.520 --> 00:15:59.216
Then there's the Debussy
music score on the piano.

251
00:15:59.240 --> 00:16:00.680
Interesting.

252
00:16:01.120 --> 00:16:03.136
Why do you keep
looking over my shoulder?

253
00:16:03.160 --> 00:16:04.240
I'm not.

254
00:16:05.360 --> 00:16:07.736
Got your table set up. Fergs.

255
00:16:07.760 --> 00:16:10.360
-What table?
-It's nothing. really.

256
00:16:10.960 --> 00:16:13.000
Hi. One second.

257
00:16:13.400 --> 00:16:17.016
Gosh. You really were serious
about moving on from Lola.

258
00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:20.560
-Don't judge me. all right?
-No judgement here.

259
00:16:22.200 --> 00:16:24.920
So sorry about all of this.

260
00:16:25.200 --> 00:16:28.976
-No. it's lovely.
-That's one word for it.

261
00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.296
Young love. eh? Don't suppose
there's much chance

262
00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:34.536
of him and Lola
getting it back on. then?

263
00:16:34.560 --> 00:16:37.336
It's a shame.
Neither of them will do better.

264
00:16:37.360 --> 00:16:39.456
Second-year English?

265
00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:42.536
-Um. that's brilliant.
-Yeah. yeah. Thanks.

266
00:16:42.560 --> 00:16:44.936
I love it. I mean some of the
texts are a bit hard but...

267
00:16:44.960 --> 00:16:46.536
I'm doing computer science.

268
00:16:46.560 --> 00:16:49.136
I'll work in my dad's business
when I graduate.

269
00:16:49.160 --> 00:16:51.976
So. what kind of work
can you get with English?

270
00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.600
I hadn't really thought of that.

271
00:16:55.360 --> 00:16:58.496
Sorry. I am... I am a partner
in a private detective agency.

272
00:16:58.520 --> 00:17:00.016
I did mention that.

273
00:17:00.040 --> 00:17:02.040
But what do you want to do
for a real job?

274
00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:04.896
I like five-year plans.

275
00:17:04.920 --> 00:17:07.776
Five years in education.
then I'll get my first job.

276
00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:11.296
become manager within those five
years. but also get married.

277
00:17:11.320 --> 00:17:13.816
I want to be married
by the time I'm 26.

278
00:17:13.840 --> 00:17:16.096
Because. well. I'll still look
good in a wedding dress.

279
00:17:16.120 --> 00:17:17.456
but be mature enough.

280
00:17:17.480 --> 00:17:20.416
Er... I... 26?

281
00:17:20.440 --> 00:17:22.176
Wow. Wowee.

282
00:17:22.200 --> 00:17:25.776
I-I... don't remember
you mentioning any of that

283
00:17:25.800 --> 00:17:27.600
on your profile. Lottie.

284
00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:32.440
Well. you're clearly somebody
who takes romance seriously.

285
00:17:33.320 --> 00:17:35.136
And I date for life.

286
00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:38.360
I am gonna get another drink.

287
00:17:39.320 --> 00:17:40.680
Oh. wait. you...

288
00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:45.136
You know when people tell you
to be wary of dating sites?

289
00:17:45.160 --> 00:17:46.856
Not the love of your life. then.

290
00:17:46.880 --> 00:17:49.696
Don't worry.
I'll set off the fire alarm.

291
00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:53.216
Won't be the first time I've had
to jump in for a fellow soldier.

292
00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:55.456
Thank you. You know what. I think
we should get back onto the case.

293
00:17:55.480 --> 00:17:58.056
-Is there anything you need me to do?
-I'm getting back on the case.

294
00:17:58.080 --> 00:18:00.456
I need to speak with Pierce.

295
00:18:00.480 --> 00:18:03.720
And you're going to be a
gentleman and finish your date.

296
00:18:04.160 --> 00:18:07.040
And. Glenn? No fire alarms.

297
00:18:07.720 --> 00:18:10.360
Fair enough. I tried.

298
00:18:27.640 --> 00:18:30.136
-Thank you for seeing me.
-No.

299
00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:32.856
No. it's me who should be
thanking you for taking the case.

300
00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:35.856
I'm not sure you should be thanking
me yet. we haven't got anywhere.

301
00:18:35.880 --> 00:18:39.680
but if you're right about there
being another tattoo to come...

302
00:18:40.120 --> 00:18:42.360
-The clock is ticking.
-Yeah.

303
00:18:45.760 --> 00:18:47.440
Um...

304
00:18:48.440 --> 00:18:50.296
Er...

305
00:18:50.320 --> 00:18:54.440
Am I in the way?
Do you have any family due?

306
00:18:55.400 --> 00:18:57.600
-Your partner?
-No.

307
00:18:58.480 --> 00:19:00.080
No partner.

308
00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:04.040
Here.

309
00:19:07.600 --> 00:19:10.856
Well. we're hoping to have
a lead on the tattoos.

310
00:19:10.880 --> 00:19:14.040
but I wanted to ask you about
this piece of music that he's using.

311
00:19:15.120 --> 00:19:17.400
It clearly means something.

312
00:19:18.360 --> 00:19:21.376
Whether to the victims...

313
00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:24.440
Or the person tattooing them.

314
00:19:25.960 --> 00:19:28.960
Well. we're trying to find
something that links them. but...

315
00:19:29.880 --> 00:19:32.760
It's difficult
without the Garda files.

316
00:19:33.240 --> 00:19:35.776
And normally I would ask my son.

317
00:19:35.800 --> 00:19:39.640
but I doubt that you want him
knowing that you came to us.

318
00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:41.640
It's probably best.

319
00:19:53.960 --> 00:19:56.856
"Your soul is a choice landscape

320
00:19:56.880 --> 00:20:01.480
in which there roam charming
maskers and bergamaskers.

321
00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:04.776
Playing the lute.

322
00:20:04.800 --> 00:20:06.840
and dancing as if...

323
00:20:08.320 --> 00:20:11.600
"sad beneath
their fantastical disguises."

324
00:20:13.440 --> 00:20:15.080
Paul Verlaine?

325
00:20:15.440 --> 00:20:17.256
Yeah. that's right.

326
00:20:17.280 --> 00:20:22.080
Debussy based his piece
on his poem. <i>Clair de Lune.</i>

327
00:20:22.400 --> 00:20:24.840
The ache of love
in the calm moonlight?

328
00:20:25.920 --> 00:20:28.496
Debussy said. in his music.

329
00:20:28.520 --> 00:20:32.640
"you should be able to glimpse
the moon through the trees".

330
00:20:35.760 --> 00:20:38.800
The landscape being
the soul of his beloved.

331
00:20:39.560 --> 00:20:41.376
That's right.

332
00:20:41.400 --> 00:20:45.136
The piece is either sad
or happy.

333
00:20:45.160 --> 00:20:47.440
depending on how you look at it.

334
00:20:48.840 --> 00:20:54.616
So. murder because of a...
a broken love affair?

335
00:20:54.640 --> 00:20:58.016
Or perhaps some type
of perverted love?

336
00:20:58.040 --> 00:21:01.360
Maybe he was obsessed
with each of them?

337
00:21:08.760 --> 00:21:11.440
So. how long have you been
living in Ireland?

338
00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:14.536
A long time.

339
00:21:14.560 --> 00:21:16.616
Did you move here for work

340
00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:20.240
or love or the glorious weather?

341
00:21:21.760 --> 00:21:23.600
This and that.

342
00:21:24.920 --> 00:21:27.480
What made you want
to become a pathologist?

343
00:21:28.640 --> 00:21:30.360
You know.

344
00:21:31.040 --> 00:21:33.560
You like solving mysteries.
Me too.

345
00:21:34.760 --> 00:21:38.040
And... death is full of them.

346
00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:44.560
Listen. I'm sorry. but...

347
00:21:46.080 --> 00:21:48.456
I should call it a night.

348
00:21:48.480 --> 00:21:51.240
I've got to get
a good start in the morning.

349
00:21:51.680 --> 00:21:55.040
-OK.
-Let me walk you to your car.

350
00:21:56.120 --> 00:21:58.800
No. I can see myself out.

351
00:22:15.560 --> 00:22:18.360
Harry? Yeah. the tattoo guy
just messaged me.

352
00:22:18.800 --> 00:22:20.560
Yeah. I'll see you in ten.

353
00:22:21.360 --> 00:22:22.936
Do we need a plan?

354
00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:25.776
Setanta said
this Apollo guy is really weird.

355
00:22:25.800 --> 00:22:27.400
How weird could he be?

356
00:22:30.080 --> 00:22:33.016
So. er... about these tattoos.

357
00:22:33.040 --> 00:22:36.080
Do not move.
do not speak. do not breathe.

358
00:22:36.440 --> 00:22:38.560
I have to get this just right.

359
00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:50.000
Yeah. It's a masterpiece!

360
00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.176
It's like the inside
of a serial killer's head.

361
00:22:54.200 --> 00:22:56.360
My hearing is excellent!

362
00:22:57.520 --> 00:22:58.760
And this?

363
00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:01.856
This will make me
in the region of 200 grand.

364
00:23:01.880 --> 00:23:03.800
We're in the wrong business!

365
00:23:04.760 --> 00:23:08.816
The only reason you're here
is that you mentioned Jess.

366
00:23:08.840 --> 00:23:11.720
Who are you and why are you
asking about her?

367
00:23:12.080 --> 00:23:15.000
She had a tattoo.
and we think it's one of yours.

368
00:23:16.320 --> 00:23:18.616
An expert spoke
with my colleague here

369
00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:21.280
and says he could see
your signature in it.

370
00:23:21.560 --> 00:23:24.960
Clearly it was me.
or I wouldn't have texted you.

371
00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:27.216
Which expert sent you to me?

372
00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:29.656
There's no loyalty
in tattooing any more.

373
00:23:29.680 --> 00:23:31.440
No honour. no integrity.

374
00:23:31.840 --> 00:23:34.336
Can you tell us
why she had this tattoo.

375
00:23:34.360 --> 00:23:37.440
and why that musical bar?

376
00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:41.976
A tattoo is a private choice.
a whispering of the soul.

377
00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:43.656
Why are you asking?

378
00:23:43.680 --> 00:23:46.136
We're consulting with
the state pathologist's office.

379
00:23:46.160 --> 00:23:48.536
-Consulting about what?
-Accidental deaths.

380
00:23:48.560 --> 00:23:50.576
What can you tell us about Jess?

381
00:23:50.600 --> 00:23:54.680
Why would I tell you anything
about her? Who are you. really?

382
00:23:55.360 --> 00:23:57.536
-We told you. we're...
-Right. leave.

383
00:23:57.560 --> 00:23:59.096
-No. Excuse me...
-Liars.

384
00:23:59.120 --> 00:24:01.176
I have no time for liars.

385
00:24:01.200 --> 00:24:04.496
My time is precious
and undervalued.

386
00:24:04.520 --> 00:24:06.720
-Leave.
-OK. OK.

387
00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:09.600
Look. hey. we just want to...

388
00:24:10.560 --> 00:24:11.760
Talk to you.

389
00:24:12.800 --> 00:24:15.736
Well. that went well.
Bitter indeed.

390
00:24:15.760 --> 00:24:18.096
His face softened
when he looked at that tattoo.

391
00:24:18.120 --> 00:24:20.760
I think Jess Boylan
meant something to him.

392
00:24:23.120 --> 00:24:25.536
We're on Jess's side.

393
00:24:25.560 --> 00:24:29.280
This is our business card.
if you want to check us out.

394
00:24:35.840 --> 00:24:37.000
Leave!

395
00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:39.256
We'll leave it on the mat.

396
00:24:39.280 --> 00:24:41.200
just in case
you change your mind.

397
00:24:41.840 --> 00:24:43.856
Right. we're getting nowhere
and we still have no idea

398
00:24:43.880 --> 00:24:45.896
if or when this killer
is gonna strike again.

399
00:24:45.920 --> 00:24:48.656
Don't I know it?!
I'll talk to Jess's husband.

400
00:24:48.680 --> 00:24:50.056
See if he knows Apollo.

401
00:24:50.080 --> 00:24:52.136
Yeah. and I'll speak to Sam.
Bev's ex.

402
00:24:52.160 --> 00:24:53.776
See if Apollo did her tattoo.

403
00:24:53.800 --> 00:24:55.896
You never know.
maybe he was having an off day.

404
00:24:55.920 --> 00:24:57.656
What about Chris's mother?

405
00:24:57.680 --> 00:24:59.696
Well. the only thing
we'll get from that

406
00:24:59.720 --> 00:25:02.336
is her request for a doctor.
I think we'll skip that.

407
00:25:02.360 --> 00:25:03.440
Yeah.

408
00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:12.176
Jess used to help me with the
artwork I had to do for the kids.

409
00:25:12.200 --> 00:25:13.896
Turns out I'm rubbish at it.

410
00:25:13.920 --> 00:25:16.456
Oh. I don't know.
Looks like an abstract. is it?

411
00:25:16.480 --> 00:25:19.240
Like a car or a head or...?

412
00:25:22.720 --> 00:25:25.680
This guy is the man
I wanted to ask about.

413
00:25:26.680 --> 00:25:29.336
Yes. Yeah. I do recognise him.
Why?

414
00:25:29.360 --> 00:25:32.800
Ah. I'll tell you. but first.
where do you know him from?

415
00:25:33.240 --> 00:25:35.056
This is gonna sound
a little weird.

416
00:25:35.080 --> 00:25:36.936
but I think he was stalking
Jess a bit.

417
00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:40.440
What does "a bit" of stalking
look like?

418
00:25:40.800 --> 00:25:44.240
I saw him outside the house
and then at the funeral.

419
00:25:44.600 --> 00:25:46.760
And then again at the grave.

420
00:25:47.160 --> 00:25:48.816
That's only when I spotted him.

421
00:25:48.840 --> 00:25:51.136
I don't know
if there were other times.

422
00:25:51.160 --> 00:25:53.440
He's the one
that did Jess's tattoo.

423
00:25:54.320 --> 00:25:55.840
What does that mean?

424
00:25:56.200 --> 00:25:58.416
I've been thinking about that
since our last chat

425
00:25:58.440 --> 00:26:00.416
and all the questions
you've been asking.

426
00:26:00.440 --> 00:26:02.656
Do you think
something happened to Jess?

427
00:26:02.680 --> 00:26:04.576
Her death was an accident. right?

428
00:26:04.600 --> 00:26:07.376
All the people at the hospital
were really lovely

429
00:26:07.400 --> 00:26:10.040
and it really did seem
like a freak event.

430
00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:13.120
I mean. honestly. I don't know.

431
00:26:13.560 --> 00:26:15.240
But I'm going to find out.

432
00:26:17.280 --> 00:26:19.240
Do I need to go to the police?

433
00:26:19.720 --> 00:26:24.360
Well. it's up to you. but
I'd leave it with us for now.

434
00:26:25.720 --> 00:26:27.400
I'll stay in touch with you.

435
00:26:32.560 --> 00:26:34.760
I told you. I don't know him.

436
00:26:35.320 --> 00:26:37.616
Just noticed you go in
for tattoos yourself.

437
00:26:37.640 --> 00:26:40.776
I got these in the States.
I don't know that guy.

438
00:26:40.800 --> 00:26:42.776
And I had no idea
Bev even had a tattoo.

439
00:26:42.800 --> 00:26:45.096
I told you she was into fitness
and all that craic.

440
00:26:45.120 --> 00:26:48.176
She wouldn't even get a belly
piercing. let alone a tattoo.

441
00:26:48.200 --> 00:26:50.616
I see you have Debussy
on the piano over there.

442
00:26:50.640 --> 00:26:52.176
You happen
to have <i>Claire de Lune?</i>

443
00:26:52.200 --> 00:26:53.656
What the hell's this about?

444
00:26:53.680 --> 00:26:56.136
I looked you up.
You're a private detective.

445
00:26:56.160 --> 00:26:58.936
Why are you questioning me
like I did something to Bev?

446
00:26:58.960 --> 00:27:01.576
Those photos I showed you.
you recognised them.

447
00:27:01.600 --> 00:27:02.880
What photos?

448
00:27:05.400 --> 00:27:09.440
A man and a woman.
Chris O'Neill and Jess Boylan.

449
00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:13.216
I don't know
what you're talking about.

450
00:27:13.240 --> 00:27:15.696
Fine. Let's just get
the Guards down here to ask.

451
00:27:15.720 --> 00:27:17.616
You're right.
I am a private investigator.

452
00:27:17.640 --> 00:27:19.616
and I'm pretty sure
Bev was murdered.

453
00:27:19.640 --> 00:27:21.640
And those other people.

454
00:27:22.400 --> 00:27:24.496
By the way. how's your
liquor licence. in date?

455
00:27:24.520 --> 00:27:27.080
Because I just happen to know
the Chief Superintendent.

456
00:27:27.640 --> 00:27:29.656
What? Wait.

457
00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:31.296
OK.

458
00:27:31.320 --> 00:27:32.696
-OK.
-Yes?

459
00:27:32.720 --> 00:27:35.600
I don't know him.
Like. know-know.

460
00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:38.336
OK. Which one?

461
00:27:38.360 --> 00:27:41.240
The photo you showed me
last time. the man.

462
00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:43.720
-Chris?
-Yeah.

463
00:27:44.240 --> 00:27:47.480
I never met him.
but I saw him once.

464
00:27:47.960 --> 00:27:51.016
-When?
-When he and my fiancée

465
00:27:51.040 --> 00:27:54.080
were going into a hotel
together. holding hands.

466
00:27:54.600 --> 00:27:56.376
Chris and Bev
were having an affair?

467
00:27:56.400 --> 00:27:59.376
She said he was a client.
and he was. I think.

468
00:27:59.400 --> 00:28:01.336
but he was giving her
more than casework.

469
00:28:01.360 --> 00:28:02.856
And you didn't confront them?

470
00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:04.336
I've never wanted
to be a member of a club

471
00:28:04.360 --> 00:28:06.056
that doesn't want me.

472
00:28:06.080 --> 00:28:07.976
When she got home that night.
I had her stuff packed.

473
00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:09.560
She was dead to me.

474
00:28:11.480 --> 00:28:12.760
I don't mean dead.

475
00:28:14.440 --> 00:28:17.040
Do you know
why Chris was her client?

476
00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:21.376
No. Bev worked for herself.

477
00:28:21.400 --> 00:28:24.376
She had a secretary.
young guy. Vincent Castle.

478
00:28:24.400 --> 00:28:27.600
I think he's over in London
now. I'll get you his contact details.

479
00:28:29.200 --> 00:28:31.040
Yeah. I'd appreciate it.

480
00:28:35.320 --> 00:28:36.920
Well. it's progress.

481
00:28:37.480 --> 00:28:39.080
To where. I don't know.

482
00:28:39.480 --> 00:28:41.640
At least we have a link
for two of them.

483
00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:45.816
We should find out
why she was representing him.

484
00:28:45.840 --> 00:28:47.680
Could be for anything.

485
00:28:48.120 --> 00:28:50.136
Driving offence. I don't know.

486
00:28:50.160 --> 00:28:51.936
Look. we should find out
what Chris did

487
00:28:51.960 --> 00:28:54.216
before he became
a full-time carer.

488
00:28:54.240 --> 00:28:57.080
You know. in case he sued
his boss or something.

489
00:28:57.960 --> 00:28:59.976
Ooh.

490
00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:01.160
Charlie.

491
00:29:03.840 --> 00:29:06.656
Lola's been nominated
for a student award!

492
00:29:06.680 --> 00:29:08.400
Best Of The Year!

493
00:29:10.200 --> 00:29:13.496
Oh. it's really worked out
for her going to Georgetown.

494
00:29:13.520 --> 00:29:15.520
Hasn't it just.

495
00:29:16.040 --> 00:29:19.576
-You should be proud of her.
-What? Yeah. of course I am.

496
00:29:19.600 --> 00:29:22.536
-We're all proud of her.
-Very much so.

497
00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:24.440
I'm the proudest...

498
00:29:26.720 --> 00:29:29.976
What is it? You're doing
that thing with your face.

499
00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:31.896
That "thinking look" thing.

500
00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:33.336
-Doctor.
-What?

501
00:29:33.360 --> 00:29:36.640
-"Doctor. doctor."
-Are you having a stroke?

502
00:29:37.760 --> 00:29:40.096
-I am just such an idiot.
-What?

503
00:29:40.120 --> 00:29:43.016
That's why he was so able
to take care of her.

504
00:29:43.040 --> 00:29:45.696
Look. I have no idea
what you're on about.

505
00:29:45.720 --> 00:29:47.536
Chris O'Neill's mother. Greta.

506
00:29:47.560 --> 00:29:49.896
all she ever said
was "doctor. doctor".

507
00:29:49.920 --> 00:29:52.056
Yeah.
because she wanted a doctor.

508
00:29:52.080 --> 00:29:53.360
No!

509
00:29:54.120 --> 00:29:57.480
Because she was so proud
of the one she already had.

510
00:29:58.040 --> 00:29:59.680
Already had?

511
00:30:01.200 --> 00:30:05.240
Her son. And Jess died
on the operating table.

512
00:30:08.760 --> 00:30:10.696
Mark. this is Harry Wild.

513
00:30:10.720 --> 00:30:13.136
Would you call me
as soon as you get this?

514
00:30:13.160 --> 00:30:17.080
I need to ask you a little more
about Jess's operation.

515
00:30:22.920 --> 00:30:24.616
How's it going?

516
00:30:24.640 --> 00:30:27.176
I've left a message for the guy
who used to work with Bev.

517
00:30:27.200 --> 00:30:29.816
And I left multiple messages
with Apollo.

518
00:30:29.840 --> 00:30:31.976
the angriest tattoo artist
in the land.

519
00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:34.216
And I made inquiries
into Chris O'Neill.

520
00:30:34.240 --> 00:30:36.496
so we'll find out soon
if you were right.

521
00:30:36.520 --> 00:30:38.136
But it feels like
you're getting somewhere.

522
00:30:38.160 --> 00:30:41.496
Or nowhere. If there really is
another victim out there.

523
00:30:41.520 --> 00:30:44.096
-or there's going to be one...
-Then we need to move faster.

524
00:30:44.120 --> 00:30:45.416
And if we're right
about Chris...

525
00:30:45.440 --> 00:30:47.079
We might have come at this
all wrong.

526
00:30:49.720 --> 00:30:51.560
Apollo.

527
00:30:52.560 --> 00:30:54.176
Hello? Yes.

528
00:30:54.200 --> 00:30:56.040
Yes. we can do that.

529
00:30:56.960 --> 00:30:58.640
Do you know the Hairy Goose?

530
00:30:59.640 --> 00:31:01.800
We can meet you there
in an hour.

531
00:31:16.520 --> 00:31:18.936
Sometimes I have to quiet
the muses.

532
00:31:18.960 --> 00:31:21.376
Their voices. they get so loud.

533
00:31:21.400 --> 00:31:25.136
-I can't imagine.
-Why did you want to meet us?

534
00:31:25.160 --> 00:31:26.776
I asked around about you two.

535
00:31:26.800 --> 00:31:29.016
It seems you're good
at what you do.

536
00:31:29.040 --> 00:31:32.880
despite your absolute inability
to tell the truth.

537
00:31:33.240 --> 00:31:36.920
-We're... sorry?
-You were very fond of Jess.

538
00:31:37.480 --> 00:31:40.616
Fond. In love.
Is there a difference?

539
00:31:40.640 --> 00:31:42.360
Oh. quite a bit.

540
00:31:42.720 --> 00:31:45.216
Women like Jess
don't come along every day.

541
00:31:45.240 --> 00:31:48.216
She had a softness to her.

542
00:31:48.240 --> 00:31:50.600
An innocence. a gentility.

543
00:31:51.200 --> 00:31:53.400
We were twin souls.

544
00:31:53.680 --> 00:31:57.656
Artistic spirits
separated by the universe.

545
00:31:57.680 --> 00:32:00.840
-He didn't deserve her.
-Mark?

546
00:32:01.280 --> 00:32:03.496
I think he was very much
in love with her.

547
00:32:03.520 --> 00:32:04.976
Then why didn't he stop her

548
00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:08.536
from having that
completely pointless operation?

549
00:32:08.560 --> 00:32:10.096
She was perfection.

550
00:32:10.120 --> 00:32:12.616
Love isn't about stopping people
doing what they want.

551
00:32:12.640 --> 00:32:15.800
-It's about allowing them to.
-Nonsense!

552
00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:17.776
If you want to help.

553
00:32:17.800 --> 00:32:20.736
tell us why Jess chose
that particular tattoo.

554
00:32:20.760 --> 00:32:22.936
That's simple. Her mother.

555
00:32:22.960 --> 00:32:24.616
What about her mother?

556
00:32:24.640 --> 00:32:26.736
-Jacqueline Brody.
-I'm lost.

557
00:32:26.760 --> 00:32:29.056
She's a famous piano player.

558
00:32:29.080 --> 00:32:33.736
Oh. he gets it -
this strange. handsome man.

559
00:32:33.760 --> 00:32:36.096
-Who are you?
-I am Pierce.

560
00:32:36.120 --> 00:32:37.640
Doesn't matter.

561
00:32:38.280 --> 00:32:42.696
<i>Claire de Lune</i> was one
of Jacqueline's showcases.

562
00:32:42.720 --> 00:32:45.096
It was Jess's
favourite piece. too.

563
00:32:45.120 --> 00:32:49.280
She had it as a lullaby.
How do you not know this?

564
00:32:49.640 --> 00:32:52.496
Are you sure you do actually
solve these cases?

565
00:32:52.520 --> 00:32:54.976
Mark says that she didn't play.
He didn't say anything

566
00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:57.296
about Jess and her mother being
obsessed with <i>Clair de Lune.</i>

567
00:32:57.320 --> 00:32:58.856
There's no way
he wouldn't know that.

568
00:32:58.880 --> 00:33:00.936
And I checked out Chris.

569
00:33:00.960 --> 00:33:03.216
He worked at
Crocus Health and Beauty.

570
00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:06.856
which is a small hospital that
specialises in plastic surgery.

571
00:33:06.880 --> 00:33:08.776
So. if he was Jess's doctor...

572
00:33:08.800 --> 00:33:10.136
There's no way that Mark
wouldn't know about that.

573
00:33:10.160 --> 00:33:12.376
What's happening?
Why are you so excited?

574
00:33:12.400 --> 00:33:15.456
It's positively disgusting
how happy you all look.

575
00:33:15.480 --> 00:33:17.496
We need to confirm all this.
but. Apollo.

576
00:33:17.520 --> 00:33:20.376
these other tattoos. can you
tell anything by looking at them?

577
00:33:20.400 --> 00:33:24.696
Yes. They're an abomination
to my craft.

578
00:33:24.720 --> 00:33:27.040
These were done by an amateur!

579
00:33:27.400 --> 00:33:29.416
-Thought as much!
-It's time to go to Charlie.

580
00:33:29.440 --> 00:33:30.856
Yep!

581
00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:33.256
No. you just stay.

582
00:33:33.280 --> 00:33:35.280
Stay here.

583
00:33:38.640 --> 00:33:42.216
I have no words. Just none.

584
00:33:42.240 --> 00:33:44.296
It's from Bev Lyons'
former secretary.

585
00:33:44.320 --> 00:33:47.256
He said she represented Chris
O'Neill in a medical liability suit

586
00:33:47.280 --> 00:33:48.696
and she won.

587
00:33:48.720 --> 00:33:50.296
Someone else was named
in the suit.

588
00:33:50.320 --> 00:33:52.976
Wait. hold up.
Who sued? The husband?

589
00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:55.136
He sued the team
that performed the operation.

590
00:33:55.160 --> 00:33:56.696
The doctor. Chris O'Neill.

591
00:33:56.720 --> 00:33:59.656
and the senior nurse
in attendance.

592
00:33:59.680 --> 00:34:01.336
Alison Melvin.

593
00:34:01.360 --> 00:34:03.096
She's to be the fourth victim.

594
00:34:03.120 --> 00:34:04.696
So. the husband. Mark.

595
00:34:04.720 --> 00:34:06.856
has been. what.
killing these people one by one

596
00:34:06.880 --> 00:34:08.616
and making it look
like accidents?

597
00:34:08.640 --> 00:34:10.256
Why is he tattooing them?

598
00:34:10.280 --> 00:34:12.256
Surely he realises that will
link him to every victim.

599
00:34:12.280 --> 00:34:14.256
This is his revenge for Jess.

600
00:34:14.280 --> 00:34:16.240
He doesn't care
if he gets caught.

601
00:34:16.600 --> 00:34:19.896
You need to warn Alison Melvin.
and you need to arrest Mark.

602
00:34:19.920 --> 00:34:23.640
-He hasn't answered my calls.
-I just hope we're on time.

603
00:34:37.280 --> 00:34:38.936
No sign of him.

604
00:34:38.960 --> 00:34:41.216
Hope we haven't
just got a search warrant

605
00:34:41.240 --> 00:34:44.640
-for an innocent man's house.
-I don't think he's innocent.

606
00:34:48.800 --> 00:34:50.896
-Is that a tattoo kit?
-Yep.

607
00:34:50.920 --> 00:34:53.520
And. worryingly.
the gun is missing.

608
00:34:54.280 --> 00:34:57.120
I don't understand.
How could he have vanished?

609
00:34:57.480 --> 00:34:59.536
Maybe because he realised
you two are getting close.

610
00:34:59.560 --> 00:35:01.736
Well. if it wasn't
for the two of us.

611
00:35:01.760 --> 00:35:04.080
you wouldn't even know
two murders had taken place.

612
00:35:05.400 --> 00:35:07.896
Look. no one can get
a hold of Alison Melvin.

613
00:35:07.920 --> 00:35:09.696
She left work
but never arrived home.

614
00:35:09.720 --> 00:35:11.240
Well. you have to find her.

615
00:35:11.840 --> 00:35:14.736
He keeps them a while.
he must do. to tattoo them.

616
00:35:14.760 --> 00:35:16.896
I know that. Mother.

617
00:35:16.920 --> 00:35:18.640
Right...

618
00:35:20.080 --> 00:35:21.976
We have a lead.

619
00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:24.976
Mark is from Mayo originally
and has a holiday place there.

620
00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:27.256
We've alerted the locals
to secure it.

621
00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:28.760
I'll head there right now.

622
00:35:32.560 --> 00:35:35.776
I don't buy it. Bev and Chris
were left in Dublin.

623
00:35:35.800 --> 00:35:37.696
He's hardly killing them in Mayo

624
00:35:37.720 --> 00:35:39.176
and then driving
all the way back.

625
00:35:39.200 --> 00:35:40.616
But what can we do?

626
00:35:40.640 --> 00:35:42.880
It's like looking
for a needle in a haystack.

627
00:35:50.160 --> 00:35:51.936
These are her paintings
on the wall.

628
00:35:51.960 --> 00:35:53.136
Oh. beautiful.

629
00:35:53.160 --> 00:35:56.440
I've got it! Come on.

630
00:36:29.480 --> 00:36:32.336
This Jacqueline Brody.
what do you know about her?

631
00:36:32.360 --> 00:36:35.176
She was a recluse.

632
00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:38.256
-Like a weirdo?
-No. not in a weird way.

633
00:36:38.280 --> 00:36:42.296
She just didn't want to be
in the limelight any more.

634
00:36:42.320 --> 00:36:46.520
So. I assume she lived
somewhere isolated?

635
00:36:47.080 --> 00:36:49.816
Like a little cottage
in the mountains somewhere?

636
00:36:49.840 --> 00:36:52.616
How do you know that?
You're right. she...

637
00:36:52.640 --> 00:36:56.016
She lived in Wicklow.
Where was it?

638
00:36:56.040 --> 00:36:58.096
I drove past one time
and I imagined her

639
00:36:58.120 --> 00:37:00.776
in there playing the piano
and. er...

640
00:37:00.800 --> 00:37:04.440
-She moved to Lough Tay.
-Sorry. how are you working this out?

641
00:37:05.280 --> 00:37:07.376
Jess was a brilliant artist.

642
00:37:07.400 --> 00:37:10.336
She had multiple paintings of
her mother's cottage in the house

643
00:37:10.360 --> 00:37:12.096
and paintings of Lough Tay.

644
00:37:12.120 --> 00:37:13.560
Pierce.

645
00:37:13.760 --> 00:37:16.160
See if you can find it
on Google Maps.

646
00:37:16.520 --> 00:37:18.416
I can certainly give it a try.

647
00:37:18.440 --> 00:37:21.216
Charlie!
He's going the wrong direction.

648
00:37:21.240 --> 00:37:22.840
On it!

649
00:37:23.280 --> 00:37:26.696
Hey. guys. Give me some time
and I'm gonna come with you.

650
00:37:26.720 --> 00:37:28.656
Time is the one thing
we don't have.

651
00:37:28.680 --> 00:37:30.456
But it could be dangerous.

652
00:37:30.480 --> 00:37:33.280
We're used to it. fella.

653
00:37:38.720 --> 00:37:41.680
Pierce is sending me
the details now.

654
00:37:59.160 --> 00:38:00.280
You're awake.

655
00:38:03.200 --> 00:38:05.000
The drug should have lasted
longer.

656
00:38:06.520 --> 00:38:09.336
Sorry about that.
we're a bit short for time

657
00:38:09.360 --> 00:38:12.040
so it looks like I'll have to do
things the other way around.

658
00:38:13.040 --> 00:38:15.960
Kill you first.
and then the tattoo.

659
00:38:26.840 --> 00:38:28.240
I know you.

660
00:38:30.200 --> 00:38:31.856
You're...

661
00:38:31.880 --> 00:38:33.856
Christ! You killed my wife

662
00:38:33.880 --> 00:38:36.240
and you can't even be bothered
to remember my name?

663
00:38:36.800 --> 00:38:38.440
I didn't kill her.

664
00:38:39.680 --> 00:38:43.456
It was an accident. a horrible
tragedy and the court...

665
00:38:43.480 --> 00:38:45.760
The courts? You're all to blame.

666
00:38:46.520 --> 00:38:48.160
You're all complicit.

667
00:38:48.760 --> 00:38:50.776
You have to pay
for what you've done.

668
00:38:50.800 --> 00:38:52.840
Police are on their way.

669
00:38:53.800 --> 00:38:55.816
It's quite common. I believe.

670
00:38:55.840 --> 00:38:59.816
nurses overdosing. especially
when they're filled with remorse

671
00:38:59.840 --> 00:39:01.560
for something
they've done wrong.

672
00:39:03.280 --> 00:39:04.640
Agh!

673
00:39:05.680 --> 00:39:07.160
Oh. God!

674
00:39:08.680 --> 00:39:11.256
I know I'm usually the one
to say we should wait. but...

675
00:39:11.280 --> 00:39:12.640
But if he's in there with her.

676
00:39:20.360 --> 00:39:22.400
-Fergus.
-On it.

677
00:39:22.760 --> 00:39:24.640
There's nowhere to go.

678
00:39:25.760 --> 00:39:27.479
You have to pay
for what you did.

679
00:39:36.400 --> 00:39:39.136
-Come here.
-Don't even think about it.

680
00:39:39.160 --> 00:39:41.040
He's stronger than he looks.

681
00:39:41.640 --> 00:39:43.856
-Hey!
-Agh!

682
00:39:43.880 --> 00:39:45.880
Easy. easy!

683
00:39:54.960 --> 00:39:57.056
He's admitted to everything.

684
00:39:57.080 --> 00:39:59.256
You were right.
He'd no end game.

685
00:39:59.280 --> 00:40:01.496
He just wanted revenge.

686
00:40:01.520 --> 00:40:03.176
Figured he was going
to either kill himself

687
00:40:03.200 --> 00:40:04.680
or end up in prison.

688
00:40:05.960 --> 00:40:07.816
-Absolutely tragic.
-Mm.

689
00:40:07.840 --> 00:40:10.640
That was impressive.
finding those tattoos.

690
00:40:11.320 --> 00:40:13.360
Saved a woman's life.

691
00:40:14.640 --> 00:40:16.240
I'll get another round in.

692
00:40:18.640 --> 00:40:21.896
"That was impressive."
"Saved a woman's life."

693
00:40:21.920 --> 00:40:24.336
Yeah. not us actually
solving the case

694
00:40:24.360 --> 00:40:26.600
or me wrestling a killer
to the ground.

695
00:40:27.720 --> 00:40:29.999
And I didn't even
have to leave my office.

696
00:40:32.960 --> 00:40:36.096
-I have to go.
-Early start?

697
00:40:36.120 --> 00:40:37.240
Yeah.

698
00:40:38.400 --> 00:40:40.880
Thanks. Thank you.

699
00:40:41.520 --> 00:40:43.176
I mean it.

700
00:40:43.200 --> 00:40:45.400
-Kid.
-Doc.

701
00:40:52.440 --> 00:40:55.040
-So. no date tonight?
-Nope.

702
00:40:55.720 --> 00:40:57.136
Given up on it?

703
00:40:57.160 --> 00:40:58.536
No. No. not at all.

704
00:40:58.560 --> 00:41:00.736
No. I've got one set up
for next week.

705
00:41:00.760 --> 00:41:02.936
Very excited.
Yeah. I can't wait.

706
00:41:02.960 --> 00:41:05.056
This one seems sane.

707
00:41:05.080 --> 00:41:07.216
Well. they all seem sane

708
00:41:07.240 --> 00:41:09.360
till you spend
a little time together.

709
00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:13.480
What about you?
You giving up after Harry B?

710
00:41:14.400 --> 00:41:16.720
Life is for living. Fergus.

711
00:41:17.320 --> 00:41:20.736
You know what they say.
Never wait for a bus or a man.

712
00:41:20.760 --> 00:41:23.200
There'll be a new one along
in five minutes.

713
00:41:23.960 --> 00:41:26.736
Wow! Aren't you romantic?

714
00:41:26.760 --> 00:41:28.440
Oh. yeah!
